Task 1

The first task should be for you to get some intuitive understanding of the distribution of ratings and the associated psychometric dimensions. How riskily are the different categories of risks (e.g., techonolgical, transportation, health) perceived? How much variance is there within each category? Consider using visualization of distributions, for example, using density plots.

Solution 1

risk_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=risk_ratings, fill=cluster)) +
  geom_density(alpha=0.4) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Solution 2

risk_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=risk_ratings, fill=cluster)) +
  geom_density(alpha=0.4) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  facet_grid(cluster ~ .) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Solution 3

risk_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=risk_ratings, y=cluster, fill=cluster)) +
  geom_density_ridges(alpha=0.4, scale=0.8) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
   theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Task 2

To what extent do the risk perception results match the classic findings on risk perception? Does a two-dimensional visual representation of risks match well the patterns by Fischhoff et al.(1978)?

Solution 1

risk_data %>%
  select(word, cluster, risk_ratings, in_Fisch, psych_pc1, psych_pc2) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=psych_pc1, y=psych_pc2, label = word)) +
  geom_point(color="red", size= 2, alpha=0.4) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ifelse(in_Fisch == "TRUE", word, "")), hjust = - 0.5) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  xlim(-8, 8) +
  ylim(-4.5, 4.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Solution 2

risk_data %>%
  select(word, cluster, risk_ratings, in_Fisch, psych_pc1, psych_pc2) %>%
  filter(in_Fisch == "TRUE") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=psych_pc1, y=psych_pc2, label = word)) +
  geom_point(size= 2, alpha=0.5) +
  geom_text(aes(label = word, color = cluster), hjust = - 0.5) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  xlim(-8, 8) +
  ylim(-5, 5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Bonus Task

How might you label psych_pc1 and psych_pc2 to make them interpretable? Which of the original 9 psychometric dimensions do the 2 principle components relate to the most?

cor_dat <- risk_data %>%
  select(psych_pc1, psych_pc2, psych_voluntary:psych_new) %>%
  drop_na()
# correlation between all items
ggcorrplot(round(cor(cor_dat, use="complete.obs"), digits=2), hc.order = FALSE, type = "lower", lab = T, outline.col = "white",
                ggtheme = ggplot2::theme_bw,
                colors = c("goldenrod2", "white", "dodgerblue4"),
                tl.cex = 8, lab_size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Correlation between components and dimensions")

Task 3

How well does the psychometric paradigm capture risk perception and how do the semantic models fare in comparison? Consider using scatter plots to examine the correlations between model predictions.

Solution 1

predict_data <- risk_data %>%
  select(risk_ratings, cluster, psych_pred_risk, glove_pred_risk, swow_pred_risk)  %>%
  pivot_longer(cols=c("psych_pred_risk", "glove_pred_risk", "swow_pred_risk"), names_to = "model", values_to = "predictions")

predict_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=risk_ratings, y=predictions, colour=model)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE) +
  scale_colour_viridis_d() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Solution 2

predict_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=risk_ratings, y=predictions, colour=model)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE) +
  scale_colour_viridis_d() +
  theme_bw() +
  facet_wrap(~model)+
  stat_cor(digits = 3, color="black") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
